<font color="#FF0000">TO ANNE, WORDS ON TRUST</font><br>
<tt>Sun Nov 16 10:24:59 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Anne,<br><br>
Trust issues weave many pervasive threads in my life.<br><br>
The specific causes of the trust issues would take many pages, if I could remember most of them! My trust issues are more globally autonomic rather than situation driven, though there are a few special triggers, like the government, for instance. That should surprise no one.<br><br>
Let it suffice to say that my Vietnam experience left a scar of absolutely no trust in anything, for starters.<br><br>
Many people have a balance between trust and distrust as a result of their life experience. My &quot;balance&quot; is skewed to the side of distrust, and sometimes to the extreme. It is a complex picture, with connections to fear based things. This leads to behavioral characteristics that can be sometimes alarming or confusing to the uninformed.<br><br>
In my line of work, for instance, I have essentially trusted no one, from time to time. To have done so would be a violation of the &quot;mission&quot;. The &quot;mission&quot; is to keep people alive and uninjured. Anyone, and I mean anyone, who has become an obstacle or is peceived as an obstacle to that end, is considered at some dark level a &quot;gook&quot; and must be neutralized. Fortunately, for me, these are non-violent things, though the air will be blue and lightning will jump from every doorknob.<br><br>
The &quot;mission&quot; is one of those 'Nam time warp loops where the essence of my 'Nam experience is distilled into my life's work. You could always trust charlie to kill, and that was about it.<br><br>
This thing also works in funny and very pathetic ways. I recently had to go get a passport, a very 'nothing' thing for anybody, but me. I automatically and uncontrollably experienced severe inertia and fear at just the thought of it, much less the trip overseas, the thought of which almost sent me into the foxhole. I did not trust the government with anything. The passport became a symbol of vulnerability, a ticket to permit the government to mess with me all over again, as if some form of primitive magic were going to cause an instant replay and I would become a slave to its diabolical purpose. My wife said I kept looking at the passport when I received it, as if something were going to jump right out of the great seal and grab me. <br><br>
Don't laugh, it really happened, and it can still trigger me severly.<br><br>
I have some of these trust issues better understood, and the automatic reactions somewhat under control, because I don't like it very much, and I am working very hard with a lot of good people to put a leash on some things. Some of those good people are &quot;government&quot;, and my overcomming that hurdle has taken me about two years, and I am still very cautious.<br><br>
That is a saga for another time.<br><br>
The fact that I can discuss this at all tells me I have gotten somewhere, but you should feel the automatic stuff rising from within as I type these words. <br><br>
PTSD, the gift that keeps on giving!<br><br>
Art<br><br>
